m, Newbury, Berkshire, England":"Thatcham, Berkshire, Anglie"},"da":{"about 1120–":"omkring 1120–Afdød","1094–Male":"1094–Afdød","1096–Male":"1096–Afdød","1115–1181":"1115–1181","1120–Male":"1120–Afdød","1126–Female":"1126–Afdød","1143–1207":"1143–1207","1070–Male":"1070–Afdød","1068–1130":"1068–1130","1143":"1143","1120":"1120","1130":"1130","1096":"1096","1094":"1094","1181":"1181","1070":"1070","1215":"1215","1126":"1126","1115":"1115","1224":"1224","1068":"1068","before 1140":"før 1140","about 1120":"omkring 1120","1207":"1207","Europe":"Europe","Wilton, Norfolk, England":"Wilton, Norfolk, England","Thatcham, Newbury, Berkshire, England":"Thatcham, Berkshire, England"},"nl":{"about 1120–":"circa 1120–Overleden","1094–Male":"1094–Overleden","1096–Male":"1096–Overleden","1115–1181":"1115–1181","1120–Male":"1120–Overleden","1126–Female":"1126–Overleden","1143–1207":"1143–1207","1070–Male":"1070–Overleden","1068–1130":"1068–1130","1143":"1143","1120":"1120","1130":"1130","1096":"1096","1094":"1094","1181":"1181","1070":"1070","1215":"1215","1126":"1126","1115":"1115","1224":"1224","1068":"1068","before 1140":"vóór 1140","about 1120":"circa 1120","1207":"1207","Europe":"Europa","Wilton, Norfolk, England":"Wilton, Norfolk, England","Thatcham, Newbury, Berkshire, England":"Thatcham, Berkshire, England"},"en":{"about 1120–":"about 1120–Deceased","1094–Male":"1094–Deceased","1096–Male":"1096–Deceased","1115–1181":"1115–1181","1120–Male":"1120–Deceased","1126–Female":"1126–Deceased","1143–1207":"1143–1207","1070–Male":"1070–Deceased","1068–1130":"1068–1130","1143":"1143","1120":"1120","1130":"1130","1096":"1096","1094":"1094","1181":"1181","1070":"1070","1215":"1215","1126":"1126","1115":"1115","1224":"1224","1068":"1068","before 1140":"before 1140","about 1120":"about 1120","1207":"1207","Europe":"Europe","Wilton, Norfolk, England":"Wilton, Norfolk, England","Thatcham, Newbury, Berkshire, England":"Thatcham, Berkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Beaufou","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: locative name in the case of the   Domesday Book   tenants from Beaufour (Calvados), which is recorded as  <i>Belfou</i>,  <i>Beaufou</i> in 1100 and as  <i>Bellefai</i> in about 1160 (   Tengvik  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Boffee","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Beaufoy  ."]},{"name":"Domesday Book","meanings":["1  English: relationship name from the Middle English personal name  <i>Bern</i>,  <i>Barn</i>. In the Midlands and East Anglia this is based on the Scandinavian personal name  <i>Biǫrn</i>, anglicized as  <i>Beorn</i>; in the south-west it is from Old English  <i>Beorn</i>; both names are from a word meaning ‘warrior’. Some of the following surname bearers may alternatively belong with other senses below.","2  English: status name from Middle English  <i>barn</i> (Old Scandinavian  <i>barn</i>) ‘child’. This term is found in   Domesday Book   as a byname for men of the upper classes; it might also have had the meaning ‘young man of a prominent family’, like Middle English  <i>child</i> (  see  Child  ).","3  English: locative name, nickname for residence near or employment at a barn, Middle English  <i>bern</i> (Old English  <i>bere-ærn</i>).  See also  Barnes  . Some of the post-medieval bearers may alternatively belong with (1) or (2)."]},{"name":"Buffey","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Beaufoy  ."]},{"name":"Boffey","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Beaufoy  ."]},{"name":"Boffy","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Beaufoy  ."]},{"name":"Tengvik","meanings":["Norman, English: locative name from Eschalles in Pas-de-Calais (see   Tengvik  , p. 87)."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":95,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":104,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard de Beaufou was born about 1120, in Wilton, Norfolk, England, his father, Ralph de Beaufou, was 51 and his mother, Agnes de Toeni, was 53. He married Mrs. Ruchard de Beaufou before 1140, in Europe. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"about 1120–":"umbes 1120–Surnud","1094–Male":"1094–Surnud","1096–Male":"1096–Surnud","1115–1181":"1115–1181","1120–Male":"1120–Surnud","1126–Female":"1126–Surnud","1143–1207":"1143–1207","1070–Male":"1070–Surnud","1068–1130":"1068–1130","1143":"1143","1120":"1120","1130":"1130","1096":"1096","1094":"1094","1181":"1181","1070":"1070","1215":"1215","1126":"1126","1115":"1115","1224":"1224","1068":"1068","before 1140":"enne 1140","about 1120":"umbes 1120","1207":"1207","Europe":"Europe","Wilton, Norfolk, England":"Wilton, Norfolk, England","Thatcham, Newbury, Berkshire, England":"Thatcham, Berkshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1120–":"noin 1120–Kuollut","1094–Male":"1094–Kuollut","1096–Male":"1096–Kuollut","1115–1181":"1115–1181","1120–Male":"1120–Kuollut","1126–Female":"1126–Kuollut","1143–1207":"1143–1207","1070–Male":"1070–Kuollut","1068–1130":"1068–1130","1143":"1143","1120":"1120","1130":"1130","1096":"1096","1094":